# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: facel-vega-fv
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus was born in French Algeria to *pied-noir* parents.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] He spent his childhood in a poor neighbourhood and later studied philosophy at the University of Algiers.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] He was in Paris when the Germans invaded France during World War II in 1940.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus tried to flee but finally joined the French Resistance where he served as editor-in-chief at *Combat*, an outlawed newspaper.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] After the war, he was a celebrity figure and gave many lectures around the world.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] He married twice but had many extramarital affairs.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus was politically active; he was part of the left that opposed Joseph Stalin and the Soviet Union because of their totalitarianism.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus was a moralist and leaned towards anarcho-syndicalism.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] He was part of many organisations seeking European integration.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] During the Algerian War (1954–1962), he kept a neutral stance, advocating a multicultural and pluralistic Algeria, a position that was rejected by most parties.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Philosophically, Camus's views contributed to the rise of the philosophy known as absurdism.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Some consider Camus's work to show him to be an existentialist, even though he himself firmly rejected the term throughout his lifetime.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Albert Camus was born on 7 November 1913 in a working-class neighbourhood in Mondovi (present-day Dréan), in French Algeria.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] His mother, Catherine Hélène Camus (née Sintès), was French with Balearic Spanish ancestry.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] He never knew his father, Lucien Camus, a poor French agricultural worker killed in action while serving with a Zouave regiment in October 1914, during World War I.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus, his mother, and other relatives lived without many basic material possessions during his childhood in the Belcourt section of Algiers.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus was a second-generation French inhabitant of Algeria, which was a French territory from 1830 until 1962.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] His paternal grandfather, along with many others of his generation, had moved to Algeria for a better life during the first decades of the 19th century.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Hence, he was called a *pied-noir* – a slang term for people of French and other European descent born in Algeria.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] His identity and poor background had a substantial effect on his later life.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Nevertheless, Camus was a French citizen and enjoyed more rights than Arab and Berber Algerians under *indigénat*.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] During his childhood, he developed a love for football and swimming.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Under the influence of his teacher Louis Germain, Camus gained a scholarship in 1924 to continue his studies at a prestigious lyceum (secondary school) near Algiers.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Germain immediately noticed his lively intelligence and his desire to learn.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] In middle school, he gave Camus free lessons to prepare him for the 1924 scholarship competition – despite the fact that his grandmother had a plan for him to be a manual worker so that he could immediately contribute to the maintenance of the family.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus maintained great gratitude and affection towards Louis Germain throughout his life and he dedicated his speech for accepting the Nobel Prize to Germain.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] In a letter dated 30 April 1959, Germain lovingly reciprocated the warm feelings towards his former pupil, calling him "my little Camus".
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus played as goalkeeper for the Racing Universitaire d'Alger junior team from 1928 to 1930.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] The sense of team spirit, fraternity, and common purpose appealed to him enormously.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] In match reports, he was often praised for playing with passion and courage.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Any football ambitions, however, disappeared when he contracted tuberculosis.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus later drew parallels between football, human existence, morality, and personal identity.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] For him, the simplistic morality of football contradicted the complicated morality imposed by authorities such as the state and church.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] In 1930, at the age of 17, Camus was diagnosed with tuberculosis.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Because it is a transmitted disease, he moved out of his home and stayed with his uncle Gustave Acault, a butcher, who influenced the young Camus.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] It was at that time he turned to philosophy, with the mentoring of his philosophy teacher Jean Grenier.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] He was impressed by ancient Greek philosophers and Friedrich Nietzsche.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] During that time, he was only able to study part time.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] To earn money, he took odd jobs, including as a private tutor, car parts clerk, and assistant at the Meteorological Institute.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] In 1933, Camus enrolled at the University of Algiers and completed his *licence de philosophie* (BA) in 1936 after presenting his thesis on Plotinus.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus developed an interest in early Christian philosophers, but Nietzsche and Arthur Schopenhauer had paved the way towards pessimism and atheism.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus also studied novelist-philosophers such as Stendhal, Herman Melville, Fyodor Dostoyevsky, and Franz Kafka.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] That same year he met Simone Hié, then a partner of Camus's friend, who later became his first wife.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] In 1934, Camus was in a relationship with Simone Hié.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Simone had an addiction to morphine, a drug she used to ease her menstrual pains.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] His uncle Gustave did not approve of the relationship, but Camus married Hié to help her fight the addiction.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] He subsequently discovered she was in a relationship with her doctor at the same time and the couple later divorced.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus joined the French Communist Party (PCF) in early 1935.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] He saw it as a way to "fight inequalities between Europeans and 'natives' in Algeria", even though he was not a Marxist.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] He explained: "We might see communism as a springboard and asceticism that prepares the ground for more spiritual activities." Camus left the PCF a year later.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] In 1936, the independence-minded Algerian Communist Party (PCA) was founded, and Camus joined it after his mentor Grenier advised him to do so.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus's main role within the PCA was to organise the *Théâtre du Travail* ('Workers' Theatre').
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus was also close to the *Parti du Peuple Algérien* (Algerian People's Party [PPA]), which was a moderate anti-colonialist/nationalist party.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] As tensions in the interwar period escalated, the Stalinist PCA and PPA broke ties.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus was expelled from the PCA for refusing to toe the party line.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] This series of events sharpened his belief in human dignity.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus's mistrust of bureaucracies that aimed for efficiency instead of justice grew.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] He continued his involvement with theatre and renamed his group *Théâtre de l'Equipe* ('Theatre of the Team').
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Some of his scripts were the basis for his later novels.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] In 1938, Camus began working for the leftist newspaper *Alger républicain* (founded by Pascal Pia), as he had strong anti-fascist feelings, and the rise of fascist regimes in Europe was worrying him.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] By then, Camus had also developed strong feelings against authoritarian colonialism as he witnessed the harsh treatment of the Arabs and Berbers by French authorities.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] *Alger républicain* was banned in 1940 and Camus flew to Paris to take a new job at *Paris-Soir* as layout editor.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] In Paris, he almost completed his "first cycle" of works dealing with the absurd and the meaningless: the novel *L'Étranger* (*The Outsider* [UK] or *The Stranger* [US]), the philosophical essay *Le Mythe de Sisyphe* (*The Myth of Sisyphus*), and the play *Caligula*.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Each cycle consisted of a novel, an essay, and a theatrical play.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Soon after Camus moved to Paris, the outbreak of World War II began to affect France.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus volunteered to join the army but was not accepted because he had once had tuberculosis.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] As the Germans were marching towards Paris, Camus fled.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] He was laid off from *Paris-Soir* and ended up in Lyon, where he married pianist and mathematician Francine Faure on 3 December 1940.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus and Faure moved back to Algeria (Oran), where he taught in primary schools.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Because of his tuberculosis, he moved to the French Alps on medical advice.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] There he began writing his second cycle of works, this time dealing with revolt – a novel, *La Peste* (*The Plague*), and a play, *Le Malentendu* (*The Misunderstanding*).
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] By 1943 he was known because of his earlier work.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] He returned to Paris, where he met and became friends with Jean-Paul Sartre.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] He also became part of a circle of intellectuals, which included Simone de Beauvoir and André Breton.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Among them was the actress María Casares, who later had an affair with Camus.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus took an active role in the underground resistance movement against the Germans during the French Occupation.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Upon his arrival in Paris, he started working as a journalist and editor of the banned newspaper *Combat*.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus used a pseudonym for his *Combat* articles and used false ID cards to avoid being captured.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] He continued writing for the paper after the liberation of France, composing almost daily editorials under his real name.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] During that period he composed four *Lettres à un Ami Allemand* ('Letters to a German Friend'), explaining why resistance was necessary.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] After the War, Camus lived in Paris with Faure, who gave birth to twins, Catherine and Jean, in 1945.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus was now a celebrated writer known for his role in the Resistance.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] He gave lectures at various universities in the United States and Latin America during two separate trips.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] He also visited Algeria once more, only to leave disappointed by the continued oppressive colonial policies, which he had warned about many times.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] During this period he completed the second cycle of his work, with the book *L'Homme révolté* (*The Rebel*).
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus attacked totalitarian communism while advocating libertarian socialism and anarcho-syndicalism.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Upsetting many of his colleagues and contemporaries in France with its rejection of communism, the book brought about the final split between Camus and Sartre.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] His relations with the Marxist Left deteriorated further during the Algerian War.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus was a strong supporter of European integration in various marginal organisations working towards that end.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] His main aim was to express the positive side of surrealism and existentialism, rejecting the negativity and the nihilism of André Breton.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus also raised his voice against the Soviet invasion of Hungary and the totalitarian tendencies of Franco's regime in Spain.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus had numerous affairs, particularly an irregular and eventually public affair with the Spanish-born actress María Casares, with whom he had extensive correspondence.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] She had a mental breakdown and needed hospitalisation in the early 1950s.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus, who felt guilty, withdrew from public life and was slightly depressed for some time.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] In 1957, Camus received the news that he was to be awarded the Nobel Prize in Literature.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] This came as a shock to him; he anticipated André Malraux would win the award.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] At age 44, he was the second-youngest recipient of the prize, after Rudyard Kipling, who was 41.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] After this he began working on his autobiography *Le Premier Homme* (*The First Man*) in an attempt to examine "moral learning".
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] He also turned to the theatre once more.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Financed by the money he received with his Nobel Prize, he adapted and directed for the stage Dostoyevsky's novel *Demons*.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] The play opened in January 1959 at the Antoine Theatre in Paris and was a critical success.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] During these years, he published posthumously the works of the philosopher Simone Weil, in the series "Espoir" ('Hope') which he had founded for Éditions Gallimard.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Weil had great influence on his philosophy, since he saw her writings as an "antidote" to nihilism.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus described her as "the only great spirit of our times".
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus died on 4 January 1960 at the age of 46, in a car accident near Sens, in Le Grand Fossard in the small town of Villeblevin.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] He had spent the New Year's holiday of 1960 at his house in Lourmarin, Vaucluse with his family and his publisher Michel Gallimard of Éditions Gallimard, along with Gallimard's wife, Janine, and daughter, Anne.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus's wife and children went back to Paris by train on 2 January, but Camus decided to return in Gallimard's luxurious Facel Vega FV2.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] The car crashed into a plane tree on a long straight stretch of the Route nationale 5 (now the RN 6 or D606).
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus, who was in the passenger seat, died instantly, while Gallimard died five days later.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Janine and Anne Gallimard were not injured.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] In 2011, Italian author Giovanni Catelli argued that Camus might have been killed by the KGB for criticizing the Soviet Union.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] In 2013, Catelli published a book on the subject.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] An English translation of it was published in 2020.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] 144 pages of a handwritten manuscript entitled **Le premier Homme** (published in English translation as *The First Man*) were found in the wreckage.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus had predicted that this unfinished novel based on his childhood in Algeria would be his finest work.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus was buried in the Lourmarin cemetery, Vaucluse, France, where he had lived.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Jean-Paul Sartre read a eulogy, paying tribute to Camus's heroic "stubborn humanism".
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus's first publication was a play called *Révolte dans les Asturies* (*Revolt in Asturias*), written with three friends in May 1936.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] The subject was the 1934 revolt by Spanish miners that was brutally suppressed by the Spanish government, resulting in 1,500 to 2,000 deaths.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] In May 1937 he wrote his first book, *L'Envers et l'Endroit* (*Betwixt and Between*, also translated as *The Wrong Side and the Right Side*).
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Both were published by Edmond Charlot's small publishing house.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus separated his work into three cycles.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Each cycle consisted of a novel, an essay, and a play.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] The first was the cycle of the absurd consisting of *L'Étranger*, *Le Mythe de Sysiphe*, and *Caligula*.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] The second was the cycle of the revolt which included *La Peste* (*The Plague*), *L'Homme révolté* (*The Rebel*), and *Les Justes* (*The Just Assassins*).
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] The third, the cycle of the love, consisted of *Nemesis*.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Each cycle was an examination of a theme with the use of a pagan myth and including biblical motifs.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] The books in the first cycle were published between 1942 and 1944, but the theme was conceived earlier, at least as far back as 1936.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] With this cycle, Camus aimed to pose a question on the human condition, discuss the world as an absurd place, and warn humanity of the consequences of totalitarianism.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus began his work on the second cycle while he was in Algeria, in the last months of 1942, just as the Germans were reaching North Africa.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] In the second cycle, Camus used Prometheus, who is depicted as a revolutionary humanist, to highlight the nuances between revolution and rebellion.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] He analyses various aspects of rebellion, its metaphysics, and its connection to politics, and then examines it under the lens of modernity, historicity, and the absence of a God.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] After receiving the Nobel Prize, Camus gathered, clarified, and published his pacifist leaning views at *Actuelles III: Chronique algérienne 1939–1958* (*Algerian Chronicles*).
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] He then decided to distance himself from the Algerian War as he found the mental burden too heavy.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] He turned to theatre and the third cycle which was about love and the goddess Nemesis, the Greek and Roman goddess of Revenge.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Two of Camus's works were published posthumously.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] The first entitled *La mort heureuse* (*A Happy Death*) (1971) is a novel that was written between 1936 and 1938.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] It features a character named Patrice Mersault, comparable to *The Stranger*'s Meursault.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] There is scholarly debate about the relationship between the two books.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] The second was an unfinished novel, *Le Premier homme* (*The First Man*, published in 1994), which Camus was writing before he died.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] It was an autobiographical work about his childhood in Algeria and its publication in 1994 sparked a widespread reconsideration of Camus's allegedly unrepentant colonialism.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus was a moralist; he claimed morality should guide politics.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] While he did not deny that morals change over time, he rejected the classical Marxist view that historical material relations define morality.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus was also strongly critical of Marxism–Leninism, which he considered totalitarian, especially in the case of the Soviet Union.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus rebuked those sympathetic to the Soviet model and their "decision to call total servitude freedom".
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] A proponent of libertarian socialism, he stated that the Soviet Union was not socialist and the United States was not liberal.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] His critique of the Soviet Union caused him to clash with others on the political left, most notably with his on-again/off-again friend Jean-Paul Sartre.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Active in the French Resistance to the Nazi occupation of France during World War II, Camus wrote for and edited the Resistance journal *Combat*.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus had anarchist sympathies, which intensified in the 1950s, when he came to believe that the Soviet model was morally bankrupt.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus was firmly against any kind of exploitation, authority, or property, as well as the State and centralization.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] However, he opposed revolution, separating the rebel from the revolutionary and believing that the belief in "absolute truth", most often assuming the guise of history or reason, inspires the revolutionary and leads to tragic results.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] He believed that rebellion is spurred by our outrage over the world's lack of transcendent significance, while political rebellion is our response to attacks against the dignity and autonomy of the individual.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus opposed political violence, tolerating it only in rare and very narrowly defined instances, as well as revolutionary terror, which he accused of sacrificing innocent lives on the altar of history.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] David Sherman considers Camus an anarcho-syndicalist.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Graeme Nicholson considers Camus an existentialist anarchist.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] The anarchist André Prudhommeaux first introduced him at a meeting of the *Cercle des Étudiants Anarchistes* ('Anarchist Student Circle') in 1948 as a sympathiser familiar with anarchist thought.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus kept a neutral stance during the Algerian Revolution (1954–1962).
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] While he was against the violence of the National Liberation Front (FLN), he acknowledged the injustice and brutalities imposed by colonialist France.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] He was supportive of Pierre Mendès France's Unified Socialist Party (PSU) and its approach to the crisis; Mendès France advocated for reconciliation.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus also supported a like-minded Algerian militant, Aziz Kessous.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus traveled to Algeria to negotiate a truce between the two belligerents but was met with distrust by all parties.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] In one often-misquoted incident, Camus confronted an Algerian critic during his 1957 Nobel Prize acceptance speech in Stockholm, rejecting the false equivalence of justice with revolutionary terrorism: "People are now planting bombs in the tramways of Algiers.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] My mother might be on one of those tramways.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] If that is justice, then I prefer my mother." Critics have labelled the response as reactionary and a result of a colonialist attitude.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus was sharply critical of the proliferation of nuclear weapons and the bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] In the 1950s, Camus devoted his efforts to human rights.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] In 1952, he resigned from his work for UNESCO when the UN accepted Spain, under the leadership of the caudillo General Francisco Franco, as a member.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus maintained his pacifism and resisted capital punishment anywhere in the world.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] He wrote an essay against capital punishment in collaboration with Arthur Koestler, the writer, intellectual, and founder of the League Against Capital Punishment, entitled *Réflexions sur la peine capitale* ('Reflections on Capital Punishment'), published by Calmann-Levy in 1957.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Along with Albert Einstein, Camus was one of the sponsors of the Peoples' World Convention (PWC), also known as Peoples' World Constituent Assembly (PWCA), which took place between 1950 and 1951 at Palais Electoral in Geneva, Switzerland.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Born in Algeria to French parents, Camus was familiar with the institutional racism of France against Arabs and Berbers, but he was not part of a rich elite.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] He lived in very poor conditions as a child, but was a citizen of France and as such was entitled to citizens' rights; members of the country's Arab and Berber majority were not.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus was a vocal advocate of the "new Mediterranean Culture".
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] This was his vision of embracing the multi-ethnicity of the Algerian people, in opposition to "Latinité", a popular pro-fascist and antisemitic ideology among other *pieds-noirs* – French or other Europeans born in Algeria.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] For Camus, this vision encapsulated the Hellenic humanism which survived among ordinary people around the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] His 1938 address on "The New Mediterranean Culture" represents Camus's most systematic statement of his views at this time.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus also supported the Blum–Viollette proposal to grant Algerians full French citizenship in a manifesto with arguments defending this assimilative proposal on radical egalitarian grounds.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] In 1939, Camus wrote a stinging series of articles for the *Alger républicain* on the atrocious living conditions of the inhabitants of the Kabylie highlands.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] He advocated for economic, educational, and political reforms as a matter of emergency.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] In 1945, following the Sétif and Guelma massacre after Arabs revolted against French mistreatment, Camus was one of only a few mainland journalists to visit the colony.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] He wrote a series of articles reporting on conditions and advocating for French reforms and concessions to the demands of the Algerian people.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] When the Algerian War began in 1954, Camus was confronted with a moral dilemma.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] He identified with the *pieds-noirs* such as his own parents and defended the French government's actions against the revolt.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] He argued the Algerian uprising was an integral part of the "new Arab imperialism" led by Egypt and an "anti-Western" offensive orchestrated by Russia to "encircle Europe" and "isolate the United States".
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Although favoring greater Algerian autonomy or even federation, though not full-scale independence, he believed the *pieds-noirs* and Arabs could co-exist.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] During the war, he advocated a civil truce that would spare the civilians.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] It was rejected by both sides, who regarded it as foolish.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Behind the scenes, he began working for imprisoned Algerians who faced the death penalty.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] His position drew much criticism from the left and later postcolonial literary critics, such as Edward Said, who were opposed to European imperialism and charged that Camus's novels and short stories are plagued with colonial depictions – or conscious erasures – of Algeria's Arab population.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] In their eyes, Camus was no longer the defender of the oppressed.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus once said that the troubles in Algeria "affected him as others feel pain in their lungs".
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Even though Camus is mostly connected to absurdism, he is routinely categorized as an existentialist, a term he rejected on several occasions.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus himself said his philosophical origins lay in ancient Greek philosophy, Nietzsche, and 17th-century moralists, whereas existentialism arose from 19th- and early 20th-century philosophy such as Søren Kierkegaard, Karl Jaspers, and Martin Heidegger.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] He also said his work, *The Myth of Sisyphus*, was a criticism of various aspects of existentialism.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus rejected existentialism as a philosophy, but his critique was mostly focused on Sartrean existentialism and – though to a lesser extent – on religious existentialism.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] He thought that the importance of history held by Marx and Sartre was incompatible with his belief in human freedom.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] David Sherman and others also suggest the rivalry between Sartre and Camus also played a part in his rejection of existentialism.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] David Simpson argues further that his humanism and belief in human nature set him apart from the existentialist doctrine that existence precedes essence.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] On the other hand, Camus focused most of his philosophy around existential questions.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] The absurdity of life and that it inevitably ends in death is highlighted in his acts.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] His belief was that the absurd – life being void of meaning, or man's inability to know that meaning if it were to exist – was something that man should embrace.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] His opposition to Christianity and his commitment to individual moral freedom and responsibility are only a few of the similarities with other existential writers.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus addressed one of the fundamental questions of existentialism: the problem of suicide.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] He wrote: "There is only one really serious philosophical question, and that is suicide." Camus viewed the question of suicide as arising naturally as a solution to the absurdity of life.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Many existentialist writers have addressed the Absurd, each with their own interpretation of what it is and what makes it important.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Kierkegaard suggests that the absurdity of religious truths prevents people from reaching God rationally.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Sartre recognizes the absurdity of individual experience.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus's thoughts on the Absurd begin with his first cycle of books and the literary essay *The Myth of Sisyphus*, his major work on the subject.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] In 1942, he published the story of a man living an absurd life in *The Stranger*.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] He also wrote a play about the Roman emperor Caligula, pursuing an absurd logic, which was not performed until 1945.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] His early thoughts appeared in his first collection of essays, *Betwixt and Between*, in 1937.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Absurd themes were expressed with more sophistication in his second collection of essays, *Noces* (*Nuptials*) in 1938.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] In these essays, Camus reflects on the experience of the Absurd.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Aspects of the notion of the Absurd can also be found in *The Plague*.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus follows Sartre's definition of the Absurd: "That which is meaningless.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Thus man's existence is absurd because his contingency finds no external justification".
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] The Absurd is created because man, who is placed in an unintelligent universe, realises that human values are not founded on a solid external component; as Camus himself explains, the Absurd is the result of the "confrontation between human need and the unreasonable silence of the world".
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Even though absurdity is inescapable, Camus does not drift towards nihilism.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] But the realization of absurdity leads to the question: Why should someone continue to live?
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Suicide is an option that Camus firmly dismisses as the renunciation of human values and freedom.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Rather, he proposes we accept that absurdity is a part of our lives and live with it.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus regretted the continued reference to himself as a "philosopher of the absurd".
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] He showed less interest in the Absurd shortly after publishing *The Myth of Sisyphus*.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] To distinguish his ideas, scholars sometimes refer to the Paradox of the Absurd, when referring to "Camus's Absurd".
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus articulated the case for revolting against any kind of oppression, injustice, or whatever disrespects the human condition.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] He was cautious enough, however, to set the limits on the rebellion.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] *The Rebel* explains in detail his thoughts on the issue.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] There, he builds upon the absurd, described in *The Myth of Sisyphus*, but goes further.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] In the introduction, where he examines the metaphysics of rebellion, he concludes with the phrase "I revolt, therefore we exist" implying the recognition of a common human condition.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus also delineates the difference between revolution and rebellion and notices that history has shown that the rebel's revolution might easily end up as an oppressive regime; he therefore places importance on the morals accompanying the revolution.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus poses a crucial question: Is it possible for humans to act in an ethical and meaningful manner in a silent universe?
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] According to him, the answer is yes, as the experience and awareness of the Absurd creates the moral values and also sets the limits of our actions.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus separates the modern form of rebellion into two modes.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] First, there is the metaphysical rebellion, which is "the movement by which man protests against his condition and against the whole of creation".
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] The other mode, historical rebellion, is the attempt to materialize the abstract spirit of metaphysical rebellion and change the world.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] In this attempt, the rebel must balance between the evil of the world and the intrinsic evil which every revolt carries, and not cause any unjustifiable suffering.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Camus's novels and philosophical essays are still influential.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] After his death, interest in Camus followed the rise – and diminution – of the New Left.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] Following the collapse of the Soviet Union, interest in his alternative road to communism resurfaced.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] He is remembered for his skeptical humanism and his support for political tolerance, dialogue, and civil rights.
[src:facel-vega-fv/albert-camus] The French Post published a stamp with his likeness on 26 June 1967.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] An **automatic transmission** (**AT**) or **automatic gearbox** is a multi-speed transmission used in motor vehicles that does not require any input from the driver other than throttle position to change forward gears under normal driving conditions.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] The 1904 Sturtevant "horseless carriage gearbox" is often considered to be the first true automatic transmission.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] The first mass-produced automatic transmission was General Motors' Hydra-Matic, introduced in Oldsmobile models for the 1940 model year.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions are especially prevalent in vehicular drivetrains, particularly those subject to intense mechanical acceleration and frequent idle/transient operating conditions; commonly commercial/passenger/utility vehicles, such as buses and waste collection vehicles.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] Vehicles with internal combustion engines, unlike electric vehicles, require the engine to operate in a narrow range of rates of rotation, requiring a gearbox, operated manually or automatically, to drive the wheels over a wide range of speeds.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] Globally, 43% of new cars produced in 2015 were manual transmissions, falling to 37% by 2020.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions have long been prevalent in the United States, but only started to become common in Europe much later.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] In Europe in 1997, only 10–12% of cars had automatic transmissions.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] In 1957 over 80% of new cars in the United States had automatic transmissions.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions have been standard in large cars since at least 1974.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] By 2020 only 2.4% of new cars had manual transmissions.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] Historically, automatic transmissions were less efficient, but lower fuel prices in the US made this less of a problem than in Europe.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] In the United Kingdom, a majority of new cars have had automatic transmissions since 2020.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] Several manufacturers including Mercedes and Volvo no longer sell cars with manual transmissions.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] The growing prevalence of automatic transmissions is attributed to the increasing number of electric and hybrid cars, and the ease of integrating it with safety systems such as Autonomous Emergency Braking.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] The efficiency (power output as a percentage of input) of conventional automatic transmissions ranges from 86 to 94%.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] Manual transmissions are more fuel efficient than all but the newest automatic transmissions due to their inherently low parasitic losses (typically of about 4%) in addition to being cheaper to make, lighter, better performing, and of simpler mechanical design.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] Fuel economy worsens with lower efficiency.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] However, manual transmissions require the driver to operate the clutch and change gear whenever required.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] Real-world tests reported in 2022 found that in typical driving manual transmissions achieved 2 to 5% better fuel economy than automatics, increasing to 20% with an expert driver.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] Some laboratory tests show automatics in a better light due to the tests using a prescribed shifting pattern for manuals not always optimized for economy.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] However, on long highway journeys manual transmissions require maintaining a very specific cruising speed to optimise economy, making automatics preferable.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] The most common design of automatic transmissions is the hydraulic automatic, which typically uses planetary gearsets that are operated using hydraulics.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] The transmission is connected to the engine via a torque converter (or a fluid coupling prior to the 1960s), instead of the friction clutch used by most manual transmissions.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] A hydraulic automatic transmission uses planetary gearsets instead of the manual transmission's design of gears lined up along input, output and intermediate shafts.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] To change gears, the hydraulic automatic uses a combination of internal clutches, friction bands or brake packs.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] These devices are used to lock certain gears, thus setting which gear ratio is in use at a given time.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] A sprag clutch (a ratchet-like device which can freewheel and transmits torque in only one direction) is often used for routine gear shifts.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] The advantage of a sprag clutch is that it eliminates the sensitivity of timing a simultaneous clutch release/apply on two planetary gearsets, simply "taking up" the drivetrain load when actuated, and releasing automatically when the next gear's sprag clutch assumes the torque transfer.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] The friction bands are often used for manually selected gears (such as low range or reverse) and operate on the planetary drum's circumference.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] Bands are not applied when the drive/overdrive range is selected, the torque being transmitted by the sprag clutches instead.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] The aforementioned friction bands and clutches are controlled using automatic transmission fluid (ATF), which is pressurized by a pump and then directed to the appropriate bands/clutches to obtain the required gear ratio.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] The ATF provides lubrication, corrosion prevention, and a hydraulic medium to transmit the power required to operate the transmission.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] Made from petroleum with various refinements and additives, ATF is one of the few parts of the automatic transmission that needs routine service as the vehicle ages.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] The *main pump* which pressurises the ATF is typically a gear pump mounted between the torque converter and the planetary gear set.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] The input for the main pump is connected to the torque converter housing, which in turn is bolted to the engine's flexplate, so the pump provides pressure whenever the engine is running.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] The pressure of the ATF is regulated by a *governor* connected to the output shaft, which varies the pressure depending on the vehicle speed.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] The *valve body* inside the transmission is responsible for directing hydraulic pressure to the appropriate bands and clutches.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] It receives pressurized fluid from the main pump and consists of several spring-loaded valves, check balls, and servo pistons.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] In older automatic transmissions, the valves use the pump pressure and the pressure from a centrifugal governor on the output side (as well as other inputs, such as throttle position or the driver locking out the higher gears) to control which ratio is selected.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] As the vehicle and engine change speed, the difference between the pressures changes, causing different sets of valves to open and close.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] In more recent automatic transmissions, the valves are controlled by solenoids.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] These solenoids are computer-controlled, with the gear selection decided by a dedicated transmission control unit (TCU) or sometimes this function is integrated into the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] Modern designs have replaced the centrifugal governor with an electronic speed sensor that is used as an input to the TCU or ECU.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] Modern transmissions also factor in the amount of load on an engine at any given time, which is determined from either the throttle position or the amount of intake manifold vacuum.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] The multitude of parts, along with the complex design of the valve body, originally made hydraulic automatic transmissions much more expensive and time-consuming to build and repair than manual transmissions; however mass-production and developments over time have reduced this cost gap.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] To provide coupling and decoupling of the engine, a modern automatic transmission uses a torque converter instead of the friction clutch used in a manual transmission.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] The 1904 Sturtevant "horseless carriage gearbox" is often considered to be the first automatic transmission for motor vehicles.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] At higher engine speeds, high gear was engaged.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] As the vehicle slowed down and engine speed decreased, the gearbox would shift back to low.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] However, the transmission was prone to sudden failure, due to the transmission being unable to withstand forces from the abrupt gear changes.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] The adoption of planetary gearsets was a significant advance towards the modern automatic transmission.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] One of the first transmissions to use this design was the manual transmission fitted to the 1901–1904 Wilson-Pilcher automobile.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] This transmission was built in the United Kingdom and used two epicyclic gears to provide four gear ratios.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] A foot clutch was used for standing starts, gear selection was using a hand lever, helical gears were used (to reduce noise) and the gears used a constant-mesh design.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] A planetary gearset was also used in the 1908 Ford Model T, which was fitted with a two-speed manual transmission (without helical gears).
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] An early patent for the automatic transmission was granted to Canadian inventor Alfred Horner Munro of Regina in 1923.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] Being a steam engineer, Munro designed his device to use compressed air rather than hydraulic fluid, and so it lacked power and never found commercial application.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] In 1923, a patent was approved in the United States describing the operation of a transmission where the manual shifting of gears and manual operation of a clutch was eliminated.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] Hoffman from Chicago and was titled: *Automatic Gear Shift and Speed Control*.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] However, it would be over a decade later until automatic transmissions were produced in significant quantities.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] In the meantime, several European and British manufacturers would use preselector gearboxes, a form of manual transmission which removed the reliance on the driver's skill to achieve smooth gear shifts.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] The first automatic transmission using hydraulic fluid was developed in 1932 by two Brazilian engineers, José Braz Araripe and Fernando Lehly Lemos.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] The evolution towards mass-produced automatic transmissions continued with the 1933–1935 REO Motor Car Company *Self-Shifter* semi-automatic transmission, which automatically shifted between two forward gears in the "Forward" mode (or between two shorter gear ratios in the "Emergency low" mode).
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] Driver involvement was still required during normal driving, since standing starts required the driver to use the clutch pedal.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] This was followed in 1937 by the Oldsmobile *Automatic Safety Transmission*.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] Similar in operation to the REO *Self-Shifter*, the *Automatic Safety Transmission* shifted automatically between the two gear ratios available in the "Low" and "High" ranges and the clutch pedal was required for standing starts.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] The Chrysler *Fluid Drive*, introduced in 1939, was an optional addition to manual transmissions where a fluid coupling (similar to a torque-convertor, but without the torque multiplication) was added, to avoid the need to operate a manual clutch.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] The General Motors Hydra-Matic became the first mass-produced automatic transmission following its introduction in 1939 (1940 model year).
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] Available as an option in cars such as the Oldsmobile Series 60 and Cadillac Sixty Special, the Hydra-Matic combined a fluid coupling with three hydraulically controlled planetary gearsets to produce four forward speeds plus reverse.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] The transmission was sensitive to engine throttle position and road speed, producing fully automatic up- and down-shifting that varied according to operating conditions.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] During World War II, the Hydra-Matic was used in some military vehicles.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] The first automatic transmission to use a torque converter (instead of a fluid coupling) was the Buick Dynaflow, which was introduced for the 1948 model year.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] In normal driving, the Dynaflow used only the top gear, relying on the torque multiplication of the torque convertor at lower speeds.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] The Dynaflow was followed by the Packard Ultramatic in mid-1949 and the Chevrolet Powerglide for the 1950 model year.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] Each of these transmissions had only two forward speeds, relying on the converter for additional torque multiplication.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] In the early 1950s, BorgWarner developed a series of three-speed torque converter automatics for car manufacturers such as American Motors, Ford and Studebaker.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] Chrysler was late in developing its own true automatic, introducing the two-speed torque converter PowerFlite in 1953, and the three-speed TorqueFlite in 1956.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] The latter was the first to utilize the Simpson compound planetary gearset.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] In 1956, the General Motors Hydra-Matic (which still used a fluid coupling) was redesigned based around the use of two fluid couplings to provide smoother shifts.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] This transmission was called the *Controlled Coupling Hydra-Matic*, or "Jetaway" transmission.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] The original Hydra-Matic remained in production until the mid-1960s at GM, with the licensed Rolls-Royce Automatic transmission soldiering on until 1978 on the Rolls-Royce Phantom VI.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] In 1964, General Motors released a new transmission, the Turbo Hydramatic, a three-speed transmission which used a torque convertor.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] The Turbo Hydramatic was among the first to have the basic gear selections (*park*, *reverse*, *neutral*, *drive*, *low*) which became the standard gear selection used for several decades.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] By the late 1960s, most of the fluid-coupling two-speed and four-speed transmissions had disappeared in favor of three-speed units with torque converters.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] Also around this time, whale oil was removed from the automatic transmission fluid.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] During the 1980s, automatic transmissions with four gear ratios became increasingly common, and many were equipped with lock-up torque convertors in order to improve fuel economy.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] Electronics began to be more commonly used to control the transmission, replacing mechanical control methods such as spring-loaded valves in the valve body.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] Most systems use solenoids which are controlled by either the engine control unit, or a separate transmission control unit.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] This allows for more precise control of shift points, shift quality, lower shift times and manual control.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] The first five-speed automatic was the Jatco 5R01, introduced in 1989 by Nissan in the Cedric and Gloria, and was electronically controlled.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] The first six-speed automatic was the ZF 6HP26 transmission, which debuted in the 2002 BMW 7 Series (E65).
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] The first seven-speed automatic was the Mercedes-Benz 7G-Tronic transmission, which debuted a year later.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] In 2007, the first eight-speed transmission to reach production was the Toyota AA80E transmission.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] The first nine-speed and ten-speed transmissions were the 2013 ZF 9HP transmission and 2017 *Toyota Direct Shift-10A* (used in the Lexus LC) respectively.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] The gear selector is the input by which the driver selects the operating mode of an automatic transmission.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] A few automobiles employed a lever on the instrument panel, such as the 1955 Chrysler Corporation cars, and notably, the Corvair.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] Some automatic transmissions, especially by General Motors from 1940 to 1964, used a layout with *reverse* as the bottom position (e.g.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] Many transmissions also include positions to restrict the gear selection to the lower gears and engages the engine brake.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] These positions are often labelled "L" (low gear), "S" (second gear) or the number of the highest gear used in that position (eg 3, 2 or 1).
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] If these positions are engaged at a time when it would result in excessive engine speed, many modern transmissions disregard the selector position and remain in the higher gear.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] Many modern transmissions include modes to adjust the shift logic to prefer either power or fuel economy.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] "Sport" (also called "Power" or "Performance") modes cause gear shifts to occur at higher engine speeds, allowing higher acceleration.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] "Economy" (also called "Eco" or "Comfort") modes cause gear shifts to occur at lower engine speeds to reduce fuel consumption.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] Since the 1990s, systems to manually request a specific gear or an upshift/downshift have become more common.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] These *manumatic* transmissions offer the driver greater control over the gear selection that the traditional modes to restrict the transmission to the lower gears.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] Use of the manumatic functions are typically achieved either via paddles located beside the steering column, or "+" and "-" controls on the gear selector.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] Some cars offer drivers both methods to request a manual gear selection.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] A *continuously variable transmission* (CVT) can change seamlessly through a continuous (infinite) range of gear ratios, compared with other automatic transmissions that provide a limited number of gear ratios in fixed steps.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] The flexibility of a CVT with suitable control may allow the engine to operate at a constant angular velocity while the vehicle moves at varying speeds.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] CVTs are used in cars, tractors, UTVs, motor scooters, snowmobiles, and earthmoving equipment.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] The most common type of CVT uses two pulleys connected by a belt or chain.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] However, several other designs have also been used.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] A *dual-clutch transmission* (DCT, sometimes referred to as a *twin-clutch transmission*, or *double-clutch transmission*) uses two separate clutches for odd and even gear sets.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] The design is often similar to two separate manual transmissions with their respective clutches contained within one housing, and working as one unit.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] In most car and truck applications, the DCT functions as an automatic transmission, requiring no driver input to change gears.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] The first DCT to reach production was the *Easidrive* automatic transmission introduced on the 1961 *Hillman Minx* mid-size car.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] This was followed by various eastern European tractors through the 1970s (using manual operation via a single clutch pedal), then the *Porsche 962 C* racing car in 1985.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] The first DCT of the modern era was used in the 2003 *Volkswagen Golf R32*.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] Since the late 2000s, DCTs have become increasingly widespread, and have supplanted hydraulic automatic transmissions in various models of cars.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] Modern versions of these systems that are fully automatic in operation, such as *Selespeed* and *Easytronic*, require no driver input over gear changes or clutch operation.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] Semi-automatic versions require only partial driver input (i.e., the driver must change gears manually), while fully automatic versions require no manual driver input, whatsoever (TCU or ECU operates both the clutch system and gear shifts automatically).
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] Modern automated manual transmissions (AMT) have their roots and origins in older clutchless manual transmissions that began to appear on mass-production automobiles in the early 1930s and 1940s, prior to the introduction of hydraulic automatic transmissions.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] These systems were designed to reduce the amount of clutch or gear shifter usage required by the driver.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] These devices were intended to reduce the difficulty of operating conventional unsynchronised manual transmissions ("crash gearboxes") that were commonly used at the time, especially in stop-start driving.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] An early example of this transmission was introduced with the Hudson Commodore in 1942, called *Drive-Master*.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] Another early example of this transmission system was introduced in the 1955 Citroën DS, which used a 4-speed *BVH* transmission.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] This semi-automatic transmission used an automated clutch, which was actuated using hydraulics.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] Gear selection also used hydraulics, however, the gear ratio needs to be manually selected by the driver.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] This system was nicknamed *Citro-Matic* in the U.S.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] The first modern AMTs were introduced by BMW and Ferrari in 1997, with their *SMG* and *F1* transmissions, respectively.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] Both systems used hydraulic actuators and electrical solenoids, and a designated transmission control unit (TCU) for the clutch and shifting, plus steering wheel-mounted paddle shifters, if the driver wanted to change gear manually.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automatic-transmission] Modern fully automatic AMTs, such as *Selespeed* and *Easytronic*, have now been largely superseded and replaced by the increasingly widespread dual-clutch transmission design.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] The functional design and development of a modern motor vehicle is typically done by a large team from many different disciplines also included within automotive engineering, however, design roles are not associated with requirements for professional- or chartered-engineer qualifications.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Automotive design in this context focuses primarily on developing the visual appearance or aesthetics of vehicles, while also becoming involved in the creation of product concepts.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Automotive design as a professional vocation is practiced by designers who may have an art background and a degree in industrial design or in transportation design.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] For the terminology used in the field, see the glossary of automotive design.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] The task of the design team is usually split into three main aspects: exterior design, interior design, and color and trim design.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Graphic design is also an aspect of automotive design; this is generally shared amongst the design team as the lead designer sees fit.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] The design focuses not only on the isolated outer shape of automobile parts, but concentrates on the combination of form and function, starting from the vehicle package.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] The aesthetic value will need to correspond to ergonomic functionality and utility features as well.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Though not all the new vehicular gadgets are to be designated as factory standard items, some of them may be integral to determining the future course of any specific vehicular models.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] The design team(s) responsible for the exterior of the vehicle develops the proportions, shape, and surface details of the vehicle.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Exterior design is first done by a series of manual sketches and digital drawings.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Progressively, more detailed drawings are executed and approved by appropriate layers of management, followed by digital rendering to images.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Consumer feedback is generally sought at this point to help iteratively refine vehicle concepts according to the targeted market and will continue throughout the rest of the design refinement process.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] After more progressive refinement, industrial plasticine and or digital models are developed from and along with the drawings and images.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] The data from these models are then used to create quarter-scale and finally full-sized mock-ups of the final design.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] With three- and five-axis CNC milling machines, the clay model is first designed in a computer program and then "carved" using the machine and large amounts of clay.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Even in times of photorealistic (three-dimensional) software and virtual models on power walls, the clay model is still the most important tool for a final evaluation of the exterior design of a vehicle and, therefore, is used throughout the industry.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] The designer responsible for the vehicles' interior develops the proportions, shape, placement, and surfaces for the instrument panel, seats, door trim panels, headliner, pillar trims, etc.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Here the emphasis is on ergonomics and the comfort of the passengers.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] The procedure here is the same as with exterior design (sketch, digital model, and clay model).
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] The color and trim (or color and materials) designer is responsible for the research, design, and development of all interior and exterior colors and materials used on a vehicle.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] These include paints, plastics, fabric designs, leather, grains, carpet, headliner, wood trim, and so on.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Color, contrast, texture, and pattern must be carefully combined to give the vehicle a unique interior environment experience.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Designers work closely with exterior and interior designers.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Designers draw inspiration from other design disciplines such as industrial design, fashion, home furnishing, architecture, and sometimes product design.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Specific research is done into global trends to design for projects two to three model years in the future.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Trend boards are created from this research to keep track of design influences as they relate to the automotive industry.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] The designer then uses this information to develop themes and concepts that are then further refined and tested on the vehicle models.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] The design team also develops graphics for items, such as badges, decals, dials, switches, kick or tread strips, or liveries.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] The sketches and rendering are transformed into 3D digital surface modeling and rendering for real-time evaluation with Math data in the initial stages.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] During the development process succeeding phases will require the 3D model fully developed to meet the aesthetic requirements of a designer as well as all engineering and manufacturing requirements.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] The fully developed CAS digital model will be re-developed for manufacturing meeting the Class-A surface standards that involve both technical as well as aesthetics.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] A Product Engineering team will further develop this data.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] These modelers usually have a background in industrial design or sometimes tooling engineering in the case of some Class-A modelers.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Autodesk Alias and ICEM Surf are the two most widely used software tools for Class-A development.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Uniform surface continuity is critical to ensure Class-A surface standards.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] The continuity of the areas is between the quality grades G0 through G3, with G3 guaranteeing the cleanest patch-to-patch transitions.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] The design process occurs concurrently with other product engineers who will be engineering the styling data for meeting performance, manufacturing, and safety regulations.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] From mid-phase, back-and-forth interactions between the designers and product engineers culminate into a finished product being manufacturing-ready.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Apart from this the engineering team parallelly works in the following areas.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Product Engineering (Body In White Sheetmetal Design and Plastic engineering), NVH Development team, Prototype development, Powertrain engineering, Physical Vehicle validation, Tool and Die development, and Manufacturing process design.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] The design team for a specific model consists of a chief designer and an exterior as well as an interior designer.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] In some cases, all three roles are done by one designer.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Several junior designers are involved in the development process as well and make specific contributions all overseen by the chief designer.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Apart from this, the color and trim designer works closely with other designers.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] The clay model team and digital model team work closely with the styling team all located within the studio.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Apart from this, there would be studio heads, studio managers, and prototype engineers who would work across all teams in the studio.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] The total team size for developing a full car usually ranges from 25 to 40 members and the development time lasts for more than 24 months until signed-off for tooling and production.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] After that, a smaller team would be working until the vehicle launch.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] In the early days of the automobile, manufacturers prioritized function over form, focusing on building simple, reliable, and affordable vehicles.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Some automakers began incorporating artists to combine styling with engineering.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Visual appeal remained secondary to technical and safety advancements until the 1930s, an era that, despite its financial challenges, became a high point of creative coachbuilding.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] World War II halted the momentum, but it evolved when the industry restarted in the late 1940s, heavily influenced by the Jet Age.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] However, the artwork and models created by designers are routinely destroyed so as not to be seen by competing automakers.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Great car designers are visionary artists who can translate their ideas from sketches and models into tangible vehicles.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Their work is a blend of artistry and engineering, shaped by collaborations with engineers who help bring their creative concepts to life.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Some automobile forms have served to influence the success and careers of successive designers.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] In the United States, automotive design reached a turning point in the 1920s when the American national automobile market began reaching saturation.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] To maintain unit sales, General Motors head Alfred P.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Sloan Jr. suggested annual model-year design changes to convince car owners that they needed to buy a new replacement each year, an idea borrowed from the bicycle industry (though Sloan usually gets the credit or blame).
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Critics called his strategy planned obsolescence.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Sloan preferred the term "dynamic obsolescence".
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] This strategy had far-reaching effects on the auto business, the field of product design, and eventually the American economy.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] The smaller automakers could not maintain the pace and expense of yearly re-styling.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Henry Ford did not like the model-year change because he clung to an engineer's notions of simplicity, the economics of scale, and design integrity.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] GM surpassed Ford's sales in 1931 and became the dominant company in the industry thereafter.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] The frequent design changes also made it necessary to use a body-on-frame rather than the lighter but less adaptable monocoque design used by most European automakers.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] In the 1930s, Chrysler's innovations with aerodynamics helped launch the Chrysler Airflow in 1934, which was revolutionary and radical compared to contemporary vehicles.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] However, inadequate consumer acceptance of the advanced appearance of the cars forced a re-design of succeeding models of the Airflow.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] This marketing experience made the entire industry take note of the high risks involved in incorporating major design advancements into their production cars.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] A major influence on American auto styling and marketing was Harley Earl, who is credited with inventing the idea of a concept car, and who brought the tailfin and other aeronautical design references to auto design starting with the rear fenders of the 1948 Cadillac.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Another notable designer was Chrysler group's designer Virgil Exner, who developed the Forward look design in the mid-1950s.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Exner is also credited with using wind tunnel testing to justify incorporating tailfins, thus moving the company away from boxy-looking cars into more aerodynamic and futuristic designs that were influenced by rockets after WWII.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Other influential automotive designers include Raymond Loewy, who was responsible for a number of Studebaker vehicles such as the Avanti, and Gordon Buehrig, who was responsible for the Auburn 851, as well as the Cord 810 and 812.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Starting in the 1960s, Dick Teague, who spent most of his career with American Motors Corporation (AMC), originated the concept of using interchangeable body panels so as to create a wide array of different vehicles using the same stampings, starting with the AMC Cavalier.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Teague was responsible for automotive designs such as the two-seat AMC AMX muscle car, the subcompact Gremlin, the Pacer, and Matador coupe, as well as the original and market segment-creating, Jeep Cherokee.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Additionally during the 1960s, Ford's first-generation Ford Mustang and Thunderbird marked another era leading into new market segments from Detroit.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] The Ford Mustang achieved record sales in its first year of production and established the pony car segment.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Personal injury litigation has affected the design and appearance of the car in the 20th century.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Until World War I, most automakers were concerned with mechanical reliability rather than the external appearance of their cars.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Later, luxury and aesthetics became a demand, and also an effective marketing tool.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Designs from each nation with their own strong cultural identity are reflected in their exterior and interior designs.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] World War II slowed the progress, but after the early 1950s, Italian designers set the trend and remained the driving force until the early part of the 1980s.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] In France notable designs came from Bugatti and Avions Voisin.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Of the mass-selling cars, Citroën launched their vehicles with innovative designs and engineering, aided by the styling of Flaminio Bertoni as evident from the Citroën DS.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] After World War II, with the decline of the coachbuilding industry, French automakers (except Citroën) followed British and other popular trends until they gained financial stability.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] During the 1980s, manufacturers like Renault cultivated their own strong design identities with designers like Patrick Le Quément.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Peugeot, which was dependent on Pininfarina since the early post-war period, later established its own brand identity from the 1980s onwards.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Its other company, Citroën, still retains its distinctive French innovations for its designs.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Great Britain was Europe's leading manufacturer of automobiles until the late-1960s.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] During that era, there were more British-based automakers than in the rest of Europe combined.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] The British automobile industry catered to all segments ranging from compact, budget, sports, utility, and luxury-type cars.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Car design in Britain was markedly different from other European designs largely because British designers were not influenced by other European art or design movements, as well as the British clay modelers, used a different sweep set.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] British cars until World War II were sold in most of the British colonies.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Innovations in vehicle packaging and chassis engineering combined with global familiarity with British designs meant vehicles were acceptable to public tastes at that time.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] British skilled resources such as panel beaters, die machinists, and clay modelers were also available partly due to their involvement with the motorsport industry.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Still, during the 1960s, British manufacturers sought professional help from Italian designers and studios such as Giovanni Michelotti, Ercole Spada, and Pininfarina.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Notable British contributions to automobile designs were the Morris Mini by Alec Issigonis, several Jaguar Cars by Sir William Lyons and Malcolm Sayer, Aston Martin DB Series, and several cars from Triumph and MG.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Ford Europe, based in Great Britain, is notable for the Ford Sierra line, a work of Uwe Bahnsen, Robert Lutz, and Patrick le Quément.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Other notable British designers include William Towns for Aston Martin, and David Bache for Land Rover and Range Rover, and Ian Callum for Jaguar.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] During the complex changes in the British car industry in the 1990s and beyond, a mix of designers worked on all of the remaining mainstream brands under one design director and in one studio.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] The director most involved was Geoff Upex, with his team of Richard Woolley, Dave Saddington, George Thomson, Alan Mobberley, and Martin Peach (colour and trim).
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Germany is often considered the birthplace of industrial design with the Bauhaus School of Design, before it was closed down by the Nazi regime.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Ferdinand Porsche and his family played a significant role in German design.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Mercedes-Benz passenger cars were also in the luxury segment and played an important role in German car design.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] After the 1980s, German design evolved into a distinctive Teutonic style often to complement their highly engineered cars suited to Autobahns.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] The early German design clues of the present-day owe some part to Italian designers like Giovanni Michelotti, Ercole Spada, Bruno Sacco, and Giorgetto Giugiaro.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] During the mid- and late-20th century one of the most influential coach builders/designers in Germany was Karmann.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] German designs started gaining popularity after the 1980s, notable after the formation of Audi.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Volkswagen, which was dependent on Marcello Gandini, Giorgetto Giugiaro, and Karmann, later formed the contemporary design language along with Audi.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] BMW entered the automobile design with sporty-looking everyday sedans using Giovanni Michelotti.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] These models were later enhanced by Ercole Spada into the 1980s, and Klaus Luthe until the mid-1990s.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] The American-born designer Chris Bangle was hired by BMW in the late-1990s to redefine the brand.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Bangle incorporated new single-press technology for compound curves to add controversial styling elements to his designs.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] The Porsche family contribution was instrumental in the evolution of Porsche cars, while the Italian designer Bruno Sacco helped create various Mercedes Models from the 1960s to the 1990s.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] In Italy, Fiat and Alfa Romeo played a major role in car design.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Many coachbuilders were dependent on these two major manufacturers.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Italian manufacturers had a large presence in motorsports leading to several sport car manufacturers like Ferrari, Lancia, Lamborghini, Maserati, etc.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] During the late-1950s, Italian automobile designs gained global popularity coinciding with the modern fashion and architecture at that time around the world.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Various design and technical schools in Turin turned out designers on a large scale.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] By the late-1960s, almost all Italian coachbuilders transformed into design studios catering to automakers around the world.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] The trend continued in the 1990s when the Japanese and Korean manufacturers sourced designs from these styling studios.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Some Italian designers whose design services were sought globally include Aldo Brovarone, Giovanni Michelotti, Ercole Spada, Bruno Sacco, Marcello Gandini, Giorgetto Giugiaro, and Walter de Silva.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Sweden had Volvo and Saab as domestic automakers, and the nation's northern location required that cars needed to withstand Nordic climate conditions.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] The Scandinavian design elements are known for their minimalism and simplicity.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] One of the early original Scandinavian designs was the Saab 92001 by Sixten Sason and Gunnar Ljungström.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Koenigsegg, founded in the 1990s, became Sweden's first domestic producer of high end sports cars, with many of their models featuring in house designs by Swedish designers.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Before World War II and until the early-1990s, Czechoslovakia had a strong presence in the automotive industry with manufacturers like Škoda, Jawa, Tatra, CZ, Praga, and Zetor.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] Czech automobiles were generally known for their originality in mechanical simplicity and designs were remarkably Bohemian as evident from Tatra cars and Jawa motorcycles.
[src:facel-vega-fv/automotive-design] During the Communist regime, the design started falling back and ultimately the domestic automakers ended up as subsidiaries of EU-based companies.
[src:facel-vega-fv/burl] A **burl** (American English) or **burr** (British English) is a tree growth in which the grain has grown in a deformed manner.
[src:facel-vega-fv/burl] It is commonly found in the form of a rounded outgrowth on a tree trunk or branch that is filled with small knots from dormant buds.
[src:facel-vega-fv/burl] Burl formation is typically a result of some form of stress such as an injury or a viral or fungal infection.
[src:facel-vega-fv/burl] More scientifically, a burl is "the result of hyperplasia, a greatly abnormal proliferation of xylem production by the vascular cambium".
[src:facel-vega-fv/burl] Burls yield a very peculiar and highly figured wood sought after in woodworking, and some items may reach high prices on the wood market.
[src:facel-vega-fv/burl] Poaching of burl specimens and damaging the trees in the process poses a problem in some areas.
[src:facel-vega-fv/burl] A burl results from a tree undergoing some form of stress.
[src:facel-vega-fv/burl] It may be caused by a virus, fungus or *Agrobacterium tumefaciens* entering the plant through an injury.
[src:facel-vega-fv/burl] Most burls grow beneath the ground, attached to the roots as a type of malignancy that is generally not discovered until the tree dies or falls over.
[src:facel-vega-fv/burl] Such burls sometimes appear as groups of bulbous protrusions connected by a system of rope-like roots.
[src:facel-vega-fv/burl] Almost all burl wood is covered by bark, even if it is underground.
[src:facel-vega-fv/burl] In some tree species, burls can grow to great size.
[src:facel-vega-fv/burl] The largest, at 26 ft (8 m), occur in coast redwoods (*Sequoia sempervirens*) and can engirdle the entire trunk; when moisture is present, these burls can grow new redwood trees.
[src:facel-vega-fv/burl] One of the world's largest burls can be found in Port McNeill, British Columbia.
[src:facel-vega-fv/burl] Burls yield a very peculiar and highly figured wood, prized for its beauty and rarity.
[src:facel-vega-fv/burl] It is sought after by furniture makers, artists, and wood sculptors.
[src:facel-vega-fv/burl] There are a number of well-known types of burls (each from a particular species); these are highly valued and sliced into veneers for furniture, inlay in doors, picture frames, household objects, automobile interior paneling and trim, musical instruments, and woodturning.
[src:facel-vega-fv/burl] The prized "burr maple" is not a species of a maple, but wood from a maple's burl (burr).
[src:facel-vega-fv/burl] Birdseye maple of the sugar maple (*Acer saccharum*) superficially resembles burr maple, but the causes of the bird's eye figure are unknown.
[src:facel-vega-fv/burl] Burl wood is very hard to work with hand tools or on a lathe, because its grain is twisted and interlocked, causing it to chip and shatter unpredictably.
[src:facel-vega-fv/burl] This "wild grain" makes burl wood extremely dense and resistant to splitting, which made it valued for bowls, mallets, mauls and "beetles" or "beadles" for hammering chisels and driving wooden pegs.
[src:facel-vega-fv/burl] Because of the value of burls, ancient redwoods in national parks in the Western United States have recently been poached by thieves for their burls, including at Redwood National and State Parks.
[src:facel-vega-fv/burl] Poachers often cut off the burls from the sides of the trunks using chainsaws, which exposes the tree to infection and disease, or fell the entire tree to steal burls higher up.
[src:facel-vega-fv/burl] Because of the risk of poaching, Jeff Denny, the state park's redwood coast sector supervisor, encourages those buying burl to inquire where it came from and to ensure it was obtained legally.
[src:facel-vega-fv/burl] Legal acquisition methods for burl include trees from private land cleared for new development and from lumber companies with salvage permits.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] There are many types of car body styles.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] They vary depending on intended use, market position, location, and the era they were made.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] Lightweight off-road vehicle with sparse bodywork.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] Originally two- or four-wheeled carriages in the 19th and early 20th centuries pulled by one horse, the motorized buggies were developed in the 1960s and grew in popularity and diversity.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] A convertible allows an open-air driving experience, with the ability to provide a roof when required.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] Most convertible roofs are either a folding textile soft-top or a retractable metal roof.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] Convertibles with a metal roof are sometimes called 'retractable hardtop', 'coupé convertible', or 'coupé cabriolet'.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] Two-door car, seating up to four persons.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] Some two-door cars have only two seats, thus **two-seaters**.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] Type of SUV with a sloping roofline similar to fastback cars, That is often adopted to offer a styling advantage compared to standard SUVs.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] Manufacturers often sell them as more premium models than their standard SUV counterparts.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] Vehicle with a higher ground clearence and larger space, That is built in a unibody platform shared with standard cars.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] Originally a North American term used for vehicles that blend characteristics between two types, it evolved to be a term for SUVs built in a unibody chassis, Even though the term SUV is used to refer both to crossovers and standard SUVs due to their visual similarities.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] Car with a roofline that slopes continuously down at the back.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] The design features a single unbroken convex curve from the roof to the rear.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] Used in the U.S. in the funeral industry to carry flowers for burial services.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] Typically a coupé-style, forward-passenger compartment with an open well in the rear.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] Car with a hatch-type rear door that is hinged at the roof and opens upwards.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] The term "hatchback" can also refer to that type of rear door, which is also used on several sports cars, SUVs, and large luxury cars.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] The modification of a passenger car to provide a long cargo area for carrying a coffin or casket.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] Hearses often have large glass panels for viewing the coffin.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] A vehicle that combines characteristics and styling of a sedan with a higher ground clearance, Similar to a crossover.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] A Kammback is a car where the rear slopes downwards before being abruptly cut off with a vertical or near vertical surface.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] This reduces the aerodynamic drag, improving the efficiency, while the stil keeping its traditional shape.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] Variant of a hatchback where the roof line and the rear cargo door are more horizontal than vertical.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] A luxury-type vehicle that is typically driven by a chauffeur with a partition between the driver's compartment and the passenger's compartment.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] Limousines may also be stretched to provide more room in the rear passenger compartment.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] In some European usage, the word describes a regular four-door sedan body style.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] Vehicle designed to transport passengers in the rear seating row(s) with reconfigurable seats in two or three rows.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] Typically has a combined passenger and cargo area, a high roof, a flat floor, a sliding door for rear passengers, and high H-point seating.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] In Europe, some small minivans have been marketed as 'leisure activity vehicles'.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] Car with a distinct rear section, With the back of the passenger compartment being in an angle to the top of what is generally the baggage compartment.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] A cargo vehicle based upon passenger car chassis and typically has one row of seats with no side windows at the rear.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] A panel van is smaller than a panel truck or cargo van and is often built on a car platform.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] A panel truck is a larger version of the panel van and is often built on a heavier platform.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] In South Africa, a pickup truck is called a "bakkie".
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] An open two-seat car with emphasis on sporting appearance or character.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] Initially, an American term for a two-seat car with no weather protection, usage has spread internationally and has evolved to include two-seat convertibles.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] These form separate compartments for engine, passenger, and cargo.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] A sedan is called a "berlina" in Spanish and Italian, or a "berline" in French.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] Initially, a horse-drawn vehicle used to carry shooting parties with their equipment and game; subsequently synonymous with station wagon / estate car; and in contemporary usage a three- or five-door wagon combining features of a station wagon and a coupé.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] Type of vehicle that combines characteristics of a passenger car with a offroad vehicle, like higher ground clearence and four wheel drive.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] Has a two-box design, a large cargo area, and a rear tailgate that is hinged to open for access to the cargo area.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] The body style is similar to a hatchback car; however, station wagons are longer and are more likely to have the roofline extended to the rear of the car (resulting in a vertical rear surface to the car) to maximize the cargo space.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] In French, a station wagon is called a "break".
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] A semi-convertible style used on some sports cars, featuring a fully removable soft or hard roof panel that leaves the A and B pillars in place on the car body.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] Based on a passenger sedan chassis and has a cargo tray in the rear integrated with the passenger body (as opposed to a pickup truck, which has a separate cargo tray).
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] In Australia, the term "ute" was originally used solely for coupé utility cars; however, in recent years, it has also been used for pickup trucks.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] Has two rows of raised seats, similar to horse-drawn carriages; usually did not have front doors, a roof, or a windshield.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] The baquet ("bathtub") style was produced in the early 1900s in Europe.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] Also a marketing term used on cars built in the United States in the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] Italian two-seat sports car with either an open-top or convertible roof.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] The term was originally used for lightweight open-top racing cars from the late 1940s through the 1950s.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] Since the 1950s, the name barchetta ("little boat" in Italian) has been revived on several occasions, mostly for cars with convertible roofs that are not specifically intended for racing.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] Italian sports coupé, typically with two seats but also including 2+2 cars.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] A retractable textile roof, similar to a convertible/cabriolet.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] The difference is that where a convertible often has the B-pillar, C-pillar, and other bodywork removed, the cabrio-coach retains all bodywork to the top of the door frames and just replaces the roof skin with a retractable fabric panel.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] Some modern cars, Like the Fiat 500 (2007), featured this body style.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] An external or open-topped driver's position and an enclosed compartment for passengers.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] Although the different terms may have once had specific meanings for certain car manufacturers or countries, the terms are often used interchangeably.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] Some coupé de villes have the passengers separated from the driver in a fully enclosed compartment, while others have a canopy for the passengers and no partition between the driver and the passengers (therefore passengers enter the compartment via the driver's area).
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] Usually describes pillarless hardtops that are cars without a B-pillar often styled to give the appearance of a convertible.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] Popular in the United States from the mid 1950s through the mid 1970s.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] It also refers to a separate top that is removable and made of metal or other hard material for sports cars or small SUVs.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] A car where the rear passengers are covered by a convertible top.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] Often the driver is separated from the rear passengers with a partition, as per a limousine.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] American luxury coupés and convertibles produced from 1952 to 2007.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] The cars prioritized comfort, styling, and a high level of interior features.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] An open-roof automobile without any fixed weather protection, which was popular from the 1900s until the 1930s.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] An open-topped roadster body and a rear cargo bed.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] A light, inexpensive, open car with basic bodywork and no windshield, top, or doors.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] Most runabouts had just a single row of seats, providing seating for two passengers.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] Body style was a type of automobile body used from 1908 until the mid-1930s, which had a streamlined profile and a folding or detachable soft top.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] The design consists of a hood or bonnet line raised to be level with the car's waistline, resulting in a straight beltline from front to back.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] A style of open car built in the United States that seats four or more people.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-body-style] The style was popular from the early 1900s to the 1930s.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Governments and private organizations have developed **car classification** schemes that are used for various purposes including regulation, description, and categorization of cars.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] The International Standard ISO 3833-1977 *Road vehicles – Types – Terms and definitions* also defines terms for classifying cars.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] The following table summarises the commonly used terms of market segments and legal classifications.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Microcars and their Japanese equivalent— kei cars— are the smallest category of automobile.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Microcars straddle the boundary between car and motorbike, and are often covered by separate regulations from normal cars, resulting in relaxed requirements for registration and licensing.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Engine size is often 700 cc (43 cu in) or less, and microcars have three or four wheels.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Microcars are most popular in Europe, where they originated following World War II.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] The predecessors to micro cars are voiturettes and cycle cars.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Kei cars have been used in Japan since 1949.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] The smallest category of vehicles that are registered as normal cars is called A-segment in Europe, or "city car" in Europe and the United States.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] The United States Environmental Protection Agency defines this category as "minicompact." However, this term is not widely used.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] The equivalents of A-segment cars have been produced since the early 1920s.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] However, the category increased in popularity in the late 1950s when the original Fiat 500 and BMC Mini were released.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] The next larger category of small cars is called B-segment in Europe, supermini in the United Kingdom and subcompact in the United States.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] The size of a subcompact car is defined by the United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), as having a combined interior and cargo volume of between 85–99 cubic feet (2,410–2,800 L).
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Since the EPA's smaller minicompact category is not as commonly used by the general public, A-segment cars are sometimes called subcompacts in the United States.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] In Europe and Great Britain, the B-segment and supermini categories do not have any formal definitions based on size.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Early supermini cars in Great Britain include the 1977 Ford Fiesta and Vauxhall Chevette.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] In the United States, the first locally-built subcompact cars were the 1970 AMC Gremlin, Chevrolet Vega, and Ford Pinto.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] The largest category of small cars is called *C-segment* or *small family car* in Europe, and *compact car* in the United States.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] The size of a compact car is defined by the United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), as having a combined interior and cargo volume of 100–109 cu ft (2.8–3.1 m3).
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] In Europe, the third-largest category for passenger cars is called *D-segment* or *large family car*.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] In the United States, the equivalent term is *mid-size* or *intermediate* cars.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) defines a mid-size car as having a combined passenger and cargo volume of 110–119 cu ft (3.1–3.4 m3).
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] In Europe, the second-largest category for passenger cars is E-segment / executive car, which are usually luxury cars.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] In other countries, the equivalent terms are *full-size car* or *large car*, which are also used for relatively affordable large cars that are not considered luxury cars.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Minivan is an American car classification for vehicles that are designed to transport passengers in the rear seating rows, and have reconfigurable seats in two or three rows.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] The equivalent terms in British English are multi-purpose vehicle (MPV), people carrier, and people mover.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Minivans are often of the "one-box" or "two-box" body configuration, high roofs, flat floors, sliding doors for rear passengers, and high H-point seating.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Mini MPV is the smallest size of MPVs and the vehicles are often built on the platforms of B-segment hatchback models.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] The compact MPV size class includes vehicles between the mini MPV and large MPV (minivan) sizes.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Compact MPVs remain predominantly a European phenomenon, although they are also built and sold in many Latin American and Asian markets.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] The largest size of minivans is also referred to as "large MPV" and became popular following the introduction of the 1984 Renault Espace and Dodge Caravan.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Since the 1990s, the smaller compact MPV and mini MPV sizes of minivans have also become popular.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] If the term "minivan" is used without specifying a size, it usually refers to a large MPV.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] The premium compact class (also called subcompact executive) is the smallest category of luxury cars.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] It became popular in the mid-2000s, when European manufacturers — such as Audi, BMW, and Mercedes-Benz — introduced new entry-level models that were smaller and cheaper than their compact executive models.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] A compact executive car or a compact luxury car is a premium car larger than a *premium compact* and smaller than an *executive car*.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Compact executive cars are equivalent size to mid-size cars and are part of the D-segment in the European car classification.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] In North American terms, close equivalents are "luxury compact" and "entry-level luxury car", although the latter is also used for the smaller *premium compact cars*.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] An executive car is a premium car larger than a *compact executive* and smaller than a *full-size luxury* car.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Executive cars are classified as E-segment cars in the European car classification.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] In the United States and several other countries, the equivalent categories are full-size car (not to be confused with the European category of "full-size luxury car") or *mid-size luxury* car.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] The largest size of a luxury car is known as a *luxury saloon* in the United Kingdom and a *full-size luxury car* in the United States.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] These cars are classified as F-segment cars in the European car classification.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Vehicles in this category are often the flagship models of luxury car brands.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Cars that prioritize handling or straight-line acceleration are called sports cars or performance cars.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] However the term "sports car" is also sometimes used specifically for lightweight two-seat cars.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Sports/performance cars can either be built on unique platforms or upgraded versions of regular cars.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] The definitions for these categories are often blurred and a car may be a member of multiple categories.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Sports cars are designed to emphasize handling, performance, or the thrill of driving.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Sports cars originated in Europe in the early 1900s, with one of the first recorded usages of the term "sports car" being in *The Times* newspaper in the United Kingdom in 1919.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Sports cars started to become popular during the 1920s.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] The term was originally used for two-seat roadsters (cars without fixed roofs).
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] However, since the 1970s the term has also been used for cars with fixed roofs (which were previously considered grand tourers).
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] A *sports sedan* — also known as "sports saloon" — is a subjective term for a sedan/saloon car that is designed to have sporting performance or handling characteristics.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] A supercar – also called an exotic car – is a loosely defined description of certain high-performance sportscars.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Since the 1990s or 2000s, the term "hypercar" has come into use for the highest-performing supercars.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Passenger vehicles with off-road capability or styling features are often categorized as either off-road vehicles, sports utility vehicles, or crossover SUVs.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] There are no commonly agreed boundaries between these categories, and usage of the terms varies between countries.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] The earliest type of passenger vehicle is called an "off-roader", "four-by-four" or "four-wheel drive".
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Off-road vehicles are usually more focused on off-road capability than SUVs and crossover SUVs (often compromising their on-road ride quality or handling).
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Common features of off-road vehicles are four-wheel drive, high ground clearance, a body-on-frame (separate chassis) construction and low-range gearing.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] A sports utility vehicle (SUV) combines elements of road-going passenger vehicles with features from off-road vehicles, such as raised ground clearance and four-wheel drive.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] There is no common definition of an SUV, and usage varies between countries.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Some definitions claim that an SUV must be built on a light-truck chassis.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] However, a broader definition considers any vehicle with off-road design features as an SUV.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] In some countries — such as the United States — SUVs have been classified as "light trucks", resulting in more lenient regulations compared to passenger vehicles.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] The predecessors to SUVs date back to military and low-volume models from the late 1930s, and the four-wheel drive station wagons / carryalls that began to be introduced in 1949.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] The 1984 Jeep Cherokee (XJ) is considered to be the first SUV in the modern style.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Most SUVs produced today use unibody construction (as per passenger cars).
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] However, in the past, many SUVs used body-on-frame construction.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] A crossover SUV— also called a crossover or CUV— is a type of sports utility vehicle (SUV) that uses a unibody construction.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Crossovers are often based on a platform shared with a passenger car, as a result, they typically have better comfort and fuel economy, but less off-road capability (many crossovers are sold without all-wheel drive) than truck-based SUVs, though more so than passenger four wheels.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] There are various inconsistencies about whether vehicles are considered crossovers or SUVs, therefore the term SUV is often used as a catch-all for both crossovers and SUVs.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] These classifications can be based on body style (e.g. sedan, coupe or hatchback), number of doors or seating capacity.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Government departments often create classification systems for taxation or regulating vehicle usage (e.g. vehicles that require a specific license or are restricted to certain roads).
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Some jurisdictions may determine vehicle tax based upon environmental principles, such as the user pays principle.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] In Australia, the Federal Chamber of Automotive Industries publishes its classifications.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] A similar set of classes is used by the Canadian EPA.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] The classification of a three-box vehicle (sedan) is determined by its length, while the classification of a two-box car (hatchback and SUV) or MPV is determined by its wheelbase.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] In the United Kingdom, a vehicle is taxed according to the vehicle's construction, engine, weight, type of fuel, and emissions, as well as the purpose for which it is used.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] In the United States, since 2010 the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety has used a formula it developed that takes into account a combination of both vehicle footprint (length times width) and weight.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] The United States National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) separates vehicles into classes by the curb weight of the vehicle with standard equipment including the maximum capacity of fuel, oil, coolant, and air conditioning, if so equipped.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] The United States Federal Highway Administration has developed a classification system used for automatically calculating road use tolls.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] There are two broad categories depending on whether the vehicle carries passengers or commodities.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Vehicles that carry commodities are further subdivided by the number of axles and number of units, including both power and trailer units.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] The United States Environmental Protection Agency (US EPA) has developed a classification system used to compare fuel economy among similar vehicles.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Passenger vehicles are classified based on a vehicle's total interior passenger and cargo volumes.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Trucks are classified based on their gross vehicle weight rating (GVWR).
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Heavy-duty vehicles are not included in the EPA scheme.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Certain cities in the United States in the 1920s chose to exempt electric-powered vehicles because officials believed those vehicles did not cause "substantial wear upon the pavements".
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Several other segment descriptions, listed below, are used in North America.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Cars from these segments may also be sold in other countries.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] However, the usage of the terms is mostly specific to North America.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Muscle car is an American term for high-performance cars, usually rear-wheel drive and fitted with a large and powerful V8 engine.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] The term originated for the 1960s and early 1970s special editions of mass-production cars which were designed for drag racing.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Pony car is an American class of automobile launched and inspired by the Ford Mustang in 1964.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] It broke all post-World War II automobile sales records, "creating the 'pony car' craze soon adopted by competitors." The term describes an affordable, compact, highly styled car with a sporty or performance-oriented image.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] A personal luxury car is a North American market segment for premium coupé or convertible produced from 1952–2007.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] These two-door cars prioritized comfort, styling, and a high level of interior features.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Not prioritizing maximum interior space, interior volumes are equivalent size to mid-size cars and are part of the D-segment in the European car classification, and exterior dimensions can exceed F-segment.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] A sporting version of an affordable compact car or a subcompact car.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] There is no precise definition and the description is applied for marketing purposes to a wide variety of models.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Cars began to be marketed as sport compacts in the mid-1980s when it was used for option packages on American-built coupes.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Since then, it has also been used for standalone sports car models and cars imported from Europe and Asia.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] However, sport compacts are not restricted to just hatchback body styles.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Several other segment descriptions, listed below, are used in Europe.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] However, the usage of the terms is mostly specific to Europe.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] A grand tourer (GT) is a car that is designed for high-speed and long-distance driving, due to a combination of performance and luxury attributes.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] The most common format is a front-engine, rear-wheel-drive two-door coupé with either a two-seat or a 2+2 arrangement.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] The term derives from the Italian language phrase *gran turismo* which became popular in the English language from the 1950s, evolving from fast touring cars and streamlined closed sports cars during the 1930s.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Hot hatch (shortened from hot hatchback) is a high-performance version of a mass-produced hatchback car.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] However, factory high-performance versions of hatchbacks have been produced since the 1970s.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Front-mounted petrol engines, together with front-wheel drive, are the most common powertrain layout.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] However, all-wheel drive has become more commonly used since around 2010.
[src:facel-vega-fv/car-classification] Most hot hatches are manufactured in Europe or Asia.
[src:facel-vega-fv/chrysler-a-engine] The **Chrysler A engine** is an OHV small-block V8 gasoline engine built by Chrysler from 1956 until 1967.
[src:facel-vega-fv/chrysler-a-engine] It featured polyspherical combustion chambers, and was offered in displacements from 276.1 cu in (4.5 L) to 325.2 cu in (5.3 L), and in various high-power configurations.
[src:facel-vega-fv/chrysler-a-engine] It began to be replaced by the wedge-head LA engine in 1964, and is not related to the hemispherical-head Hemi engine of the 1950s or 1960s.
[src:facel-vega-fv/chrysler-a-engine] The A engine was released in 1956, and was used exclusively in Plymouths until 1958 and in Chryslers and Dodges from 1959 on.
[src:facel-vega-fv/chrysler-a-engine] The DeSoto and Dodge 270/315/325 poly used similar head architecture but was not related to the Plymouth A Engine, using its own heads and the same bottom end as the Dodge and Desoto Red Ram Hemi.
[src:facel-vega-fv/chrysler-a-engine] The A engine cylinder bore center distance is 4.46 in (113.3 mm), larger than the earlier Dodge-based poly engines.
[src:facel-vega-fv/chrysler-a-engine] The A engine formed the design basis of the Chrysler LA engine, evidenced in the many parts that interchange between the two engine families.
[src:facel-vega-fv/chrysler-a-engine] The **277** "Hy-Fire" was the first A-block engine, produced for 1955 in the fall of 1954 and sharing almost nothing but the basic concepts with other engines built by Chrysler.
[src:facel-vega-fv/chrysler-a-engine] It was replaced by the 301 in 1957, except for in low-priced Plaza models where it continued to be used during the 1957 model year.
[src:facel-vega-fv/chrysler-a-engine] Power for the two-barrel version is 187 hp (139 kW); this increased to 200 hp (149 kW) for the four-barrel "Power Pack" version which also came equipped with dual exhausts.
[src:facel-vega-fv/chrysler-a-engine] The Power Pack was also fitted to the Facel Vega FV3, of which 48 examples were built in 1956 and 1957.
[src:facel-vega-fv/chrysler-a-engine] These dimensions are entirely different from the 1955 Chrysler 301.
[src:facel-vega-fv/chrysler-a-engine] This engine was also installed in the 1957–1958 Facel Vega FV3B.
[src:facel-vega-fv/chrysler-a-engine] A 313 cu in (5,121 cc) version of the A engine called the **313** was produced from 1957 to 1967 primarily for Canadian and export markets.
[src:facel-vega-fv/chrysler-a-engine] The **318** is the most common version of the A engine, produced from 1957 through 1966 in the US and 1967 in some export markets when it was replaced in all markets by the LA 318.
[src:facel-vega-fv/chrysler-a-engine] Only Plymouth used this 318 in 1957 and 1958, but it was shared with Chrysler from 1959 on and Dodge from 1960 on.
[src:facel-vega-fv/chrysler-a-engine] A high-performance version called the V-800, offered in 1957 and 1958, used two four-barrel Carter carburetors to produce 290 hp (216 kW), making it the highest-output factory A engine.
[src:facel-vega-fv/chrysler-a-engine] It was used in the 1957 and 1958 Plymouth Fury, but was also an option on Plymouth models lower in the model range.
[src:facel-vega-fv/chrysler-a-engine] Bristol Cars introduced the 318 in the Mark II model of their 408 (in 1965) and continued to use it in the succeeding 409 and 410 until 1969.
[src:facel-vega-fv/chrysler-a-engine] From 1962 until early 1965, Checker used this engine for their Aerobus limousines.
[src:facel-vega-fv/chrysler-a-engine] Its actual piston displacement is 325.25 cu in (5,330 cc) but it was marketed as a 326 to avoid confusion with the Dodge Red Ram 325.
[src:facel-vega-fv/chrysler-a-engine] The 326 uses the same 3+5⁄16 in (84.1 mm) stroke as the 318, but with the largest bore of any A engine at 3+61⁄64 in (100 mm; 3.95 in).
[src:facel-vega-fv/chrysler-a-engine] It uses hydraulic valve lifters, unlike the other A engines that used solid lifters, and was used in the 1959 Dodge Coronet.
[src:facel-vega-fv/facel-vega-fv] The **Facel Vega FV/FVS** is a car produced by French automaker Facel from 1954 until 1959.
[src:facel-vega-fv/facel-vega-fv] It continued to be built until 1962 as the **HK500**.
[src:facel-vega-fv/facel-vega-fv] The Facel "Vega" was launched at the 1954 Paris Salon, although the first prototype had been completed in October 1953.
[src:facel-vega-fv/facel-vega-fv] Originally the model name was "Vega", but they gradually became "Facel Vega" with "FV" followed by a number indicating the iteration.
[src:facel-vega-fv/facel-vega-fv] By 1956, the cars were called **FVS** (for Facel Vega Sport) in the United States.
[src:facel-vega-fv/facel-vega-fv] The 1954 versions of the Facel were fitted with a DeSoto Firedome (Chrysler) 4.5 litre Hemi V8 engine, paired with either Chrysler's two-speed Powerflite automatic transmission or, at extra cost, a four-speed manual made by Pont-à-Mousson.
[src:facel-vega-fv/facel-vega-fv] At this stage, the 180 hp (132 kW) FV was capable of a top speed from 172 to 193 km/h (107 to 120 mph), depending on which rear axle ratio was installed.
[src:facel-vega-fv/facel-vega-fv] The chassis, designed by Lance Macklin, was tubular framed, featuring coil springs and double wishbones at the front, with a leaf-sprung live rear axle.
[src:facel-vega-fv/facel-vega-fv] The styling, by Daninos himself, was somewhat American and perhaps a bit heavy, with rudimentary tail fins.
[src:facel-vega-fv/facel-vega-fv] The body was an expanded version of the earlier, Facel-bodied Simca/Ford Comète.
[src:facel-vega-fv/facel-vega-fv] An abundance of stainless steel brightwork was fitted.
[src:facel-vega-fv/facel-vega-fv] The dashboard was aircraft-inspired, and one of the first to feature a middle console over the gearbox.
[src:facel-vega-fv/facel-vega-fv] On FV and FV1 models, the dashboard was entirely upholstered in leather.
[src:facel-vega-fv/facel-vega-fv] The rear seats folded flat to provide a luggage platform and additional access to the boot.
[src:facel-vega-fv/facel-vega-fv] The FV1 was also 12 cm (4.7 in) longer than the original design47 of these early FVs were built in 1954 and 1955.
[src:facel-vega-fv/facel-vega-fv] Seven were convertibles, but as these suffered from rigidity troubles all but a handful of the rest of the large two-door Facels were pillarless coupés.
[src:facel-vega-fv/facel-vega-fv] Introduced in October 1955, the **FV2** featured a panoramic (also known as a "wrap-around") windshield.
[src:facel-vega-fv/facel-vega-fv] The trompe-l'œil dashboard was metal, hand painted to look like burled wood by Marcel Bigot, the head of Facel's paint department.
[src:facel-vega-fv/facel-vega-fv] Referred to as the **FVS** in the United States, the car featured the same 4.8-litre engine as in the FV1, albeit now offering 250 hp (184 kW).
[src:facel-vega-fv/facel-vega-fv] During 1956, the 5.4-litre FV2B appeared, with 285 hp (210 kW) and substantial added torque.
[src:facel-vega-fv/facel-vega-fv] One single FV2 convertible was built and exhibited at the company's stand at the 1955 Paris Salon, while two FV2B convertibles were built in 1956 for customers in the United States.
[src:facel-vega-fv/facel-vega-fv] One FV3 convertible was also finished, in spite of Daninos' reluctance to offer the bodystyle due to its lack of rigidity.
[src:facel-vega-fv/facel-vega-fv] The FVS was also offered with a three-speed automatic, and front disc brakes were available from 1958.
[src:facel-vega-fv/facel-vega-fv] At some point a reworked, more harmonious front end was introduced for the **FV3** model, featuring what looked like twin stacked headlights but what were actually headlamps on top and auxiliaries beneath.
[src:facel-vega-fv/facel-vega-fv] Plymouth's Polyspheric 4.5-litre "277 Power Pack" engine replaced the DeSoto Hemi unit; maximum power was down to 200 hp (147 kW).
[src:facel-vega-fv/facel-vega-fv] Power steering and power brakes were both standard as of 1957.
[src:facel-vega-fv/facel-vega-fv] As Plymouth replaced the 277 engine with the bigger-bore 301 for the 1957 model year, Facel did the same and called the resulting model the **FV3B**.
[src:facel-vega-fv/facel-vega-fv] In addition to the new 253 hp (186 kW) engine, the FV3B also received new, slightly longer and wider bodywork on cars built after the first batch of twelve cars had been completed in March 1957.
[src:facel-vega-fv/facel-vega-fv] For 1958, the engine grew to 5.8 litres (**FV4**) and 325 hp (239 kW), although the earlier 4.5 and a 4.9 (**FV3/FV3B**) were still listed as available and the three models were built alongside each other.
[src:facel-vega-fv/facel-vega-fv] A four-door version, called the Excellence, was added to the lineup in 1958, but was even more rarefied than the two-door version.
[src:facel-vega-fv/facel-vega-fv] French publisher Michel Gallimard was driving his FV2 on January 4, 1960, when he lost control and crashed outside of Villeblevin.
[src:facel-vega-fv/facel-vega-fv] The crash killed him and one of his passengers, Nobel laureate Albert Camus.
[src:facel-vega-fv/facel-vega-fv] Some have speculated that the driver was not familiar with the car's handling and weight, and that contributed to the severity of the crash.
[src:facel-vega-fv/facel-vega-fv] For 1959, the **Facel Vega HK500** was introduced.
[src:facel-vega-fv/facel-vega-fv] Essentially, it was just a renamed, upgraded FVS.
[src:facel-vega-fv/facel-vega-fv] Equipped at first with the 335 hp (246 kW) 5.8-litre V8 from the FVS, the HK500 soon received a 360 hp (265 kW) 6.3 litre Chrysler V8, giving it a top speed of 147 mph (237 km/h).
[src:facel-vega-fv/facel-vega-fv] It could accelerate from 0-60 mph (97 km/h) in 8.5 seconds.
[src:facel-vega-fv/facel-vega-fv] Initially, disc brakes were optional, becoming standard in April, 1960.
[src:facel-vega-fv/facel-vega-fv] The Facel Vega II replaced the HK500 in 1962, after 489 had been built.
[src:facel-vega-fv/facel-vega-fv] Total FV/HK production was 842, or 846 depending on the source.
[src:facel-vega-fv/facel-vega-fv] Albert Camus died when the Facel Vega FV2 he was travelling in hit a tree.
